<div class="entry-content">
<p><img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-60565" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-and-man-compressed-1.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="600" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-and-man-compressed-1.jpg 1200w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-and-man-compressed-1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-and-man-compressed-1-624x312.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-and-man-compressed-1-780x390.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></p>
<p>When we have a cat in our lives, we want to make sure they are happy and well cared for. Cats are known for their independent nature and how they are feeling might not always be obvious.</p>
<p>You try to give your cat the best life possible, but perhaps there are times when you can’t seem to figure out whether your cat seems happy. Read on to find out more about the signs of a happy cat and what you need to look out for.</p>
<p><em> <style>
            .short-description .table-row{
                display: flex;
                column-gap: 20px;
                border: 1px solid rgba(240, 179, 87, 0.6);
                padding: 20px;
                margin-bottom: 15px;
            }
            .short-description .number{
                font-family: 'ProximaNova';
                font-style: normal;
                font-weight: 700;
                font-size: 53px;
                line-height: 1;
                color: #F6D19A;
                width: 70px;
                flex: none;
            }
            .short-description .item p{
                margin: 0;
                hyphens: none;
            }
            @media (max-width: 480px) {
                .short-description .number{
                    font-size: 33px;
                    width: 45px;
                }
            }
        </style>
<div class="short-description">
<div class="cliverse-short-description-title">
<h2>Quick Overview</h2>
</div>
<div class="table-row">
<div class="number">01</div>
<div class="item"><p>How a cat is feeling might not always be obvious.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="table-row">
<div class="number">02</div>
<div class="item"><p>Cats will express their happiness through their body language, vocalizations, and certain behaviors.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="table-row">
<div class="number">03</div>
<div class="item"><p>Familiarity with signs of a happy cat makes it easier to spot when something might be wrong.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
</em></p>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#1 </span>Purring</h2>
<div id="attachment_55706" style="width: 1210px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-55706" decoding="async" class="wp-image-55706 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-purr-sleep-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="600" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-purr-sleep-compressed.jpg 1200w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-purr-sleep-compressed-768x384.jpg 768w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-purr-sleep-compressed-624x312.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-purr-sleep-compressed-780x390.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /><p id="caption-attachment-55706" class="wp-caption-text">Most frequently, purring is a sign of a happy cat, especially if your cat looks relaxed while they are purring.</p></div>
<p>Cats can <u><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-is-my-cat-purring-constantly" target="_blank" rel="noopener">purr</a></u> when they are relaxed and content. But, confusingly, they can also purr when they are unwell or in pain so the context is important. If they are purring while settled in a comfortable position with their eyes gently closed, then you can be pretty certain that you have one happy cat. You might hear them purring away when you stroke them or when they are basking in a warm patch of sunlight.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/cat-vocalizations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">7 Common Cat Vocalizations And What They Mean</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#2 </span>Kneading</h2>
<div id="attachment_45638" style="width: 1210px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-45638" decoding="async" class="wp-image-45638 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/kneading-cat-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="600" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/kneading-cat-compressed.jpg 1200w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/kneading-cat-compressed-768x384.jpg 768w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/kneading-cat-compressed-624x312.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/kneading-cat-compressed-780x390.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /><p id="caption-attachment-45638" class="wp-caption-text">Cats often knead on soft surfaces or laps when they are feeling content.</p></div>
<p><u><a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-knead-and-bite-blankets" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kneading</a></u>, also known affectionately as &#8220;making biscuits,&#8221; is when a cat pushes rhythmically with alternating front paws against a person or an object while extending and retracting their claws. Seeing your cat do this is an adorable sight. They might also purr at the same time with their eyes half-closed.</p>
<p>This kneading motion is something they would have done as kittens to stimulate milk flow from their mother’s nipples. It is thought that they carry this behavior into adulthood and do so when they are in pleasurable situations.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-knead" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Knead Their Owners?</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#3 </span>Good Appetite</h2>
<div id="attachment_60294" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60294" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60294 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/calico-eating-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="466" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/calico-eating-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/calico-eating-compressed-624x415.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/calico-eating-compressed-540x360.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60294" class="wp-caption-text">Eating well is almost always a sign of a happy cat.</p></div>
<p>A happy cat will have a good, healthy appetite. They will look forward to feeding time and might show their eager anticipation by meowing and rubbing against your legs as you prepare their food. Once you have set the bowl down in front of them, they will happily eat what you have offered them.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/best-cat-food" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The 10 Best Cat Foods In 2022</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#4 </span>Consistent Sleeping Schedule</h2>
<div id="attachment_60301" style="width: 1210px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60301" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60301 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-sleep-in-pillow-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="600" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-sleep-in-pillow-compressed.jpg 1200w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-sleep-in-pillow-compressed-768x384.jpg 768w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-sleep-in-pillow-compressed-624x312.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-sleep-in-pillow-compressed-780x390.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60301" class="wp-caption-text">Happy cats sleep the right amount at the right times.</p></div>
<p>Cats are known for loving their naps. They can spend up to 20 hours a day sleeping and resting! If your cat is happy, they tend to stick to a consistent sleeping schedule. Look out for any changes.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-purr-when-they-sleep" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Purr When They Sleep? A Vet Explains</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#5 </span>Well-Kept Appearance</h2>
<div id="attachment_53172" style="width: 750px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-53172" decoding="async" class="wp-image-53172 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cat-tongues.jpg" alt="" width="740" height="416" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cat-tongues.jpg 740w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cat-tongues-624x351.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 740px) 100vw, 740px" /><p id="caption-attachment-53172" class="wp-caption-text">A clean, well-kept coat is a sign of a healthy, happy cat.</p></div>
<p>Not only do cats enjoy sleeping for many hours, but they can also spend 50% of their waking hours grooming themselves. <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/grooming-persian-cat" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Grooming</a> is serious business so a happy cat will always make sure they keep themselves in tip-top condition. An unusually unkempt coat can be cause for concern and signal an underlying medical problem.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/repetitive-and-compulsive-grooming-in-cats" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Repetitive, Excessive And Compulsive Grooming In Cats</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#6 </span>Normal Toileting Habits</h2>
<div id="attachment_55518" style="width: 1210px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-55518" decoding="async" class="wp-image-55518 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/Automatic-Litter-Box-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="600" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/Automatic-Litter-Box-compressed.jpg 1200w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/Automatic-Litter-Box-compressed-768x384.jpg 768w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/Automatic-Litter-Box-compressed-624x312.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/Automatic-Litter-Box-compressed-780x390.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /><p id="caption-attachment-55518" class="wp-caption-text">Cats instinctually want to use their litter box, so if they are going elsewhere it&#8217;s a sign there&#8217;s a problem.</p></div>
<p>A happy and content cat will use their litter box, as they are usually exceptionally clean animals. If your cat is unhappy or unwell, they might alert you by showing unusual toileting behaviors, like peeing or pooping around the house. Identify any potential sources of stress or anxiety, and look out for other signs of illness.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/lp-best-self-cleaning-litter-box-review" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The 6 Best Automatic Self Cleaning Litter Boxes</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#7 </span>Wanting To Play</h2>
<div id="attachment_60566" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60566" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60566 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-playing-1-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="466" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-playing-1-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-playing-1-compressed-624x415.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/cat-playing-1-compressed-540x360.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60566" class="wp-caption-text">Although play drive varies amongst individual cats, most happy cats enjoy playing at least a little.</p></div>
<p>A playful cat is a happy cat. They might be content playing on their own, batting, and pouncing on toys. Or they might need you to entice them with something interactive, like a wand toy. Playing is a great way for them to use their energy and reinforce the bond they have with you.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/best-cat-toys" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The 12 Best Cat Toys: Keep Your Cat Fit And Happy With These Irresistible Toys</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#8 </span>Showing Curiosity</h2>
<div id="attachment_60567" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60567" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60567 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/curious-cat-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="467" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/curious-cat-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/curious-cat-compressed-624x416.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/curious-cat-compressed-540x360.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60567" class="wp-caption-text">Cats that are unhappy for any reason won&#8217;t usually take much interest in their surroundings.</p></div>
<p>A happy cat might show signs of curiosity and an interest in what is going around them. If your cat appears engaged with their surroundings, then that is a good sign.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-play-with-their-food" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Play With Their Food?</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#9 </span>Slow Blinking</h2>
<div id="attachment_60568" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60568" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60568 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/slow-blink-cat-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="440" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/slow-blink-cat-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/slow-blink-cat-compressed-624x392.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60568" class="wp-caption-text">Slow blinks are a cat&#8217;s way of communicating their happiness with your bond.</p></div>
<p>You might have noticed your cat making <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-is-my-cat-staring-at-me" target="_blank" rel="noopener">direct eye contact</a> with you and <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/cat-blinking" target="_blank" rel="noopener">slowly blinking</a>. This can be a sign of friendliness and an indicator of positive emotions. If they are also purring and have a relaxed posture, then they are conveying their contentment.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/signs-your-cat-loves-you" target="_blank" rel="noopener">9 Unmistakable Signs Your Cat Loves You</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#10 </span>Relaxed Body Language</h2>
<div id="attachment_40618" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-40618" decoding="async" class="wp-image-40618 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/egyptian-mau.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="466" /><p id="caption-attachment-40618" class="wp-caption-text">Happy cats usually look relaxed as opposed to unhappy cats, which might look tense.</p></div>
<p>Learning to interpret your cat’s body language is a great way to find out whether they are in a good mood. If a cat is happy, they might stand with a relaxed posture or lie down and stretch out comfortably.</p>
<p>Their tail might be held upright with the tail tip curved, like a question mark. Their eyes might be gently closed and their ears in a neutral position, pointing up and facing forward.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-have-tails" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Have Tails?</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#11 </span>Social Roll</h2>
<div id="attachment_37800" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37800" decoding="async" class="wp-image-37800 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/social-rolling-small.jpg" alt="cat social rolling" width="700" height="461" /><p id="caption-attachment-37800" class="wp-caption-text">Rolling on their back and showing their belly is something cats only do when feeling very content and secure.</p></div>
<p>Has your cat ever come up to you and suddenly rolled onto their back? This is a way for them to show their happiness and affection, and can also be a playful behavior. The belly is a vulnerable area so it takes trust for a cat to expose theirs. Bear in mind that it is not always an invitation for you to give them a <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-show-their-bellies" target="_blank" rel="noopener">belly rub</a>, so a stroke of the head or a scratch behind the ears may be better options.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-roll-around-on-their-back" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Roll Around On Their Back?</a></strong></p>
</div>
<div class="su-row card-review">
<h2 style="text-align: left;"><span class="product-review-heading">#12 </span>Seeking Your Company</h2>
<div id="attachment_55189" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-55189" decoding="async" class="wp-image-55189 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-on-laptop-with-human-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="466" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-on-laptop-with-human-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-on-laptop-with-human-compressed-624x415.jpg 624w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/cat-on-laptop-with-human-compressed-540x360.jpg 540w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-55189" class="wp-caption-text">Some cats like to be nearby without touching while others enjoy physical contact.</p></div>
<p>Depending on your cat’s personality, they might seek out your company and want interaction with you when they are feeling happy. This might come in the form of coming to greet you with meows and an upright tail that is curved at the tip. Or jumping onto the sofa for cuddles. <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-does-my-cat-headbutt-me" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Head-butting you</a> is also a great way to get your attention.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-do-cats-sit-on-laptops" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why Do Cats Sit On Laptops?</a></strong></p>
</div>
<h2>Happy Cats: Final Thoughts</h2>
<div id="attachment_60569" style="width: 710px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-60569" decoding="async" class="wp-image-60569 size-full" src="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/relax-cat-compressed.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="473" srcset="https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/relax-cat-compressed.jpg 700w, https://allaboutcats.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/relax-cat-compressed-624x422.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><p id="caption-attachment-60569" class="wp-caption-text">The better you understand your cat, the closer your bond will be.</p></div>
<p>Now, you should feel more comfortable with assessing the happiness levels of your cat. Your cat’s body language, vocalizations, and behaviors give you lots of information and indicators, though they can be subtle. By having a better understanding of them, you allow yourself to become much more attuned to your cat’s emotions so that you can recognize when something might be wrong sooner rather than later.</p>
<p><strong>Also Read: <a href="https://allaboutcats.com/why-cats-like-shoes" target="_blank" rel="noopener">5 Reasons Why Cats Like Shoes So Much</a></strong></p>
<div itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
<h2 class="cliverse-faq-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">How do I know if my cat is really happy?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Some signs of happiness can be subtle. Pay attention to your cat’s body language. Do they seem to be relaxed? Are they lying down with their eyes half-closed or gently closed? Listen out for steady purring.</p>
<p>Consider whether they are interested in interacting with you and/or their surroundings. Do they seem curious and engaged? A happy cat that has their basic needs met will also have consistent lifestyle habits when it comes to eating, grooming, and toileting.</p>
</div>
 </div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">How do you tell if a cat is getting comfortable with you?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>You can tell if a cat is getting comfortable with you if they seek your company and want to interact with you more. They might rub against you or even try to groom you. When cats rub against (allorubbing) and groom each other (allogrooming), it allows for their scents to be swapped and to maintain a group scent. Cats can direct these behaviors toward people they feel friendly with.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h3 itemprop="name">What do cats look like when they are happy?</h3>
<div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<div itemprop="text">
<p>Happy cats will adopt a relaxed posture, whether they are standing, sitting, or lying down. They won’t appear to be tense or ready to spring into action. Their tail might be held upright with a curved tip or loosely down. Their eyes might be half-closed or closed gently without any tension. Their ears will be in a neutral position but might still move to pick up any noises.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
